e of the European Middle Ages. This book offers a detailed and critical analysis of how this myth emerged and developed in medieval German and Dutchliteratures, bringing to light the vast array of narratives either idealizing, if not glorifying, Charlemagne as a political and religious leader, or, at times, criticizing or even ridiculing him as a pompous and ineffectual ruler. The motif is traced from its earlest origins in chronicles, in the Kaiserchronik, through the Rolandslied and Der Stricker's Karl der Große, to his recasting as a saint in the Zürcher Buch vom Heiligen Karl. ALBRECHT CLASSEN is University Distinguished Professor of German Studies at the University of Arizona; he received the title of Grand Knight Commander of the Most Noble Order of the Three Lions in 2017, in recognition of his outstanding service to German studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDutch literaturexHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismyMiddle High German, 1050-1500. 0aKings and rulers in literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChanson de Roland.  aCharlemagne.  aFrance.  aMalagis.  aMiddle Dutch.  aMiddle Low German.  aRoland.  aepic poems.  asaint.  atranslation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800100565?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800100565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800100565/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles